snippet.textDisplay:
What this video failed to mention is the fact that if the UK were to get rid of the monarchy, they would take their crown estates with them. The crown estates, although the revenue of which is given to the government, are still owned by the royal family. Therefore, the UK government/ taxpayer would be worse off without a royal family, even though the government funds them hundreds of millions of pounds each year. Not to mention the additional immeasurable revenue they bring in from tourism etc.


Edit: I disagree with the concept of the current monarchy and think it should be abolished.

snippet.textDisplay: The information about the sovereign grant in this video is completely false! King George didn’t give up ownership of those properties, he gave up income from them, in exchange for an allowance, and only for his lifetime. The Royal family since George has always willingly upheld this agreement, and the British government takes in more from the crown properties income than they pay out through the sovereign grant. At any time, the Royal family is free to walk away from the agreement and collect the income from the crown properties themselves, and give up the much smaller income from the sovereign grant. The British tax payers aren’t footing the bill for anything related to the Royal family, they actually make money off this arrangement. Get your facts straight Vox!

snippet.textDisplay: Good video but I feel it failed to explain more about the Sovereign Grant. Most people I speak to seem to believe it is our ‘taxpayer’ money that funds the family when in reality it is a share of the profits that the Crown Estate makes. You also have to remember the Sovereign Grant is decided by parliament and a committee to keep it in check. In 2018 it made profits of ~ £320 million. 75% going to the government (the public) and 25% to the Queen. I believe it’s actually lower but was increased due to the need for deteriorating property. 75% of the grant went towards payroll and maintenance. Not just into the Queens pocket. Yet the 25% still gets labelled as ‘taxpayers’ money...I’d say that’s more of a technicality. They’re essentially self funded and provide money from the estate and all of the other benefits that come with the castles/palaces being maintained, tourism, national image, jobs etc to the public.
